1. Introduction: The Limits of Static Deterrence

The architecture of nuclear risk management has remained conceptually frozen since the Cold War. Mutual Assured Destruction (MAD), game-theoretic equilibrium models, and treaty-based verification regimes assume a world of rational unitary actors, slow communication channels, and separable strategic domains. These assumptions have collapsed.

Contemporary geopolitical systems exhibit:

· Temporal compression: Hypersonic weapons reduce decision windows to minutes
· Network coupling: Cyber-physical infrastructures create contagion pathways between previously isolated domains
· Epistemic fragmentation: Divergent sensemaking frameworks prevent shared situational awareness
· Autonomous proliferation: AI-enabled systems introduce machine-speed escalation vectors

The GNRSA responds to this transformed landscape by reframing nuclear stability not as a balance of arsenals but as a topological property of the global security network—a property that can be mathematically measured, dynamically monitored, and actively stabilized.

This document presents a rigorous mathematical framework for such stabilization. Section 2 introduces the VUNC pillars and the dynamical equations governing the system, culminating in the Global Nuclear Stability Index (GNSI). Section 3 develops the Theory of Strategic Refusal (TSR), including Byzantine‑fault‑tolerant consensus and liveness protocols. Section 4 details the triple‑layer verification architecture, addressing the proof‑generation problem with multi‑vendor TEEs. Section 5 extends the geometric escalation mapping, focusing on epistemic distance via Wasserstein metrics. Section 6 describes the open‑source foresight infrastructure with Byzantine fault tolerance. Section 7 presents operational protocols, including dynamic cooling periods and the shared reality ledger. Section 8 provides a fully worked numerical example. Section 9 outlines the long‑term vision of a planetary security nervous system. Section 10 concludes. Appendices contain mathematical notation, protocol summaries, and open research questions.

