6. Open‑Source Strategic Foresight Infrastructure

6.1 Byzantine‑Fault‑Tolerant Simulation Consensus

The war‑game engine operates as a distributed network of N compute nodes across K jurisdictions. Each node runs the same open‑source simulation code on the same input data.

Consensus Rule: A simulation output O is considered valid iff:

|{ i : output_i = O }| ≥ ⌈2N/3⌉

Where output_i is the output of node i.

Security Guarantee: An adversary wishing to manipulate the global forecast must compromise at least ⌈N/3⌉ + 1 nodes across at least ⌈K/3⌉ + 1 jurisdictions—a combinatorially difficult task.

6.2 Transparency Without Vulnerability

All code is publicly auditable. All inputs are publicly posted with timestamps. All outputs are publicly recorded. However, to prevent adversaries from using the system to predict red lines, sensitive scenario parameters can be submitted through secure multi‑party computation (MPC) protocols that compute ensemble forecasts without revealing individual inputs.

