Appendix A: Mathematical Foundations

A.1 Graph Theory and the Laplacian

Let G = (V, E, w) be a weighted directed graph with vertex set V = \{1,\dots,n\}, edge set E \subseteq V \times V, and weight function w: E \to [0,1]. For each ordered pair (i,j) with i \neq j, we set w_{ij} = w(i,j) if (i,j) \in E and w_{ij}=0 otherwise. We assume no self-loops: w_{ii}=0.

Out-degree: d_i^{\text{out}} = \sum_{j} w_{ij}
In-degree: d_i^{\text{in}} = \sum_{j} w_{ji}

The asymmetric graph Laplacian L is an n \times n matrix defined by

L_{ij} = \begin{cases}
d_i^{\text{out}} & \text{if } i=j,\\
-w_{ij} & \text{if } i \neq j.
\end{cases}

Equivalently, L = D^{\text{out}} - W, where D^{\text{out}} = \operatorname{diag}(d_1^{\text{out}},\dots,d_n^{\text{out}}) and W is the weight matrix.

For any vector x \in \mathbb{R}^n, the quadratic form

x^\top L x = \sum_{i,j} w_{ij} (x_i - x_j)^2

measures the total “disagreement” along edges, weighted by coupling strengths. In the GNRSA, this appears in the diffusion term of the dynamics and in the GNSI definition.

A.2 Derivation of the Stability Condition \beta < 1/\rho(L^{-1}W)

Consider the linearization of the deterministic dynamics around the peaceful equilibrium S^* = 0. From

\frac{dS}{dt} = -L S + \beta R(S),

with R(S)_i = \tanh\big(\sum_j w_{ij} s_j\big). Linearizing about 0 gives \tanh(y) \approx y, so

\frac{d}{dt} \delta S = -L \delta S + \beta W \delta S = (-L + \beta W) \delta S.

The equilibrium is stable iff all eigenvalues of the matrix A = -L + \beta W have negative real parts. Since L is invertible for strongly connected graphs (the usual case for strategic networks), we can write

A = L(-I + \beta L^{-1}W).

The eigenvalues of A are the eigenvalues of -I + \beta L^{-1}W multiplied by eigenvalues of L, but more directly, the condition is that the spectral radius \rho(\beta L^{-1}W) < 1 for stability of the trivial solution of the associated linear system. This is a standard result for linear differential equations: the zero solution of \dot{x} = -Lx + \beta W x is asymptotically stable iff all eigenvalues of -L + \beta W have negative real part, which is equivalent to \beta < 1 / \rho(L^{-1}W) when L is positive definite (which holds for the Laplacian with appropriate symmetrization). For a directed graph, one must consider the generalized spectral radius; however, for our purposes we adopt the condition as a sufficient stability criterion.

Proof sketch: Let \lambda be an eigenvalue of -L + \beta W with eigenvector v. Then

(-L + \beta W) v = \lambda v \quad \Rightarrow \quad L^{-1}(-L + \beta W)v = \lambda L^{-1}v \quad \Rightarrow \quad (-I + \beta L^{-1}W)v = \lambda L^{-1}v.

This is not a standard eigenvalue problem, but one can instead consider the generalized eigenvalue problem. A more rigorous approach uses the fact that for stable matrices, the spectral radius of the matrix exponential is less than 1. However, for the symmetric case (where L and W are symmetric), the condition reduces to \beta < 1/\lambda_{\max}(L^{-1}W). In the two‑actor symmetric case, L = \begin{pmatrix} w & -w \\ -w & w \end{pmatrix}, W = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & w \\ w & 0 \end{pmatrix}, then L^{-1}W has eigenvalues \pm 1, so \beta < 1 is recovered.

Thus, \beta_{\text{critical}} = 1/\rho(L^{-1}W) is the threshold beyond which the peaceful equilibrium becomes unstable, leading to a pitchfork bifurcation.

A.3 GNSI Positivity and Lyapunov Properties

A.3.1 Positivity Bound

Recall:

\text{GNSI}(t) = \sum_{i=1}^n \|s_i(t) - s^*\|^2 - \lambda \sum_{i,j=1}^n w_{ij} \|s_i(t) - s_j(t)\|^2,

where \|\cdot\| denotes the Euclidean norm in \mathbb{R}^4 (or appropriate dimension). Using the parallelogram identity,

\|s_i - s_j\|^2 \le 2\left( \|s_i - s^*\|^2 + \|s_j - s^*\|^2 \right).

Substituting into the second sum:

\sum_{i,j} w_{ij} \|s_i - s_j\|^2 \le 2\sum_{i,j} w_{ij}\left( \|s_i - s^*\|^2 + \|s_j - s^*\|^2 \right) = 2\sum_i \left( \sum_j w_{ij} + \sum_j w_{ji} \right) \|s_i - s^*\|^2.

Therefore,

\text{GNSI}(t) \ge \sum_i \left[ 1 - 2\lambda \left( \sum_j w_{ij} + \sum_j w_{ji} \right) \right] \|s_i - s^*\|^2.

A sufficient condition for \text{GNSI}(t) \ge 0 for all possible states is

\lambda \le \frac{1}{2 \max_i \left( \sum_j w_{ij} + \sum_j w_{ji} \right)}.

In practice we set \lambda = \frac{1}{4 \max_i (\sum_j w_{ij} + \sum_j w_{ji})} to guarantee positivity with a safety margin.

A.3.2 Lyapunov Property

We claim that for \beta < \beta_{\text{critical}}, \text{GNSI}(t) is a Lyapunov function for the deterministic system in a neighborhood of the stable equilibrium, i.e., \frac{d}{dt}\text{GNSI}(t) \le 0 along trajectories, with equality only at the equilibrium.

Proof outline: Compute the time derivative using the chain rule:

\frac{d}{dt}\text{GNSI} = 2\sum_i (s_i - s^*)^\top \dot{s}_i - 2\lambda \sum_{i,j} w_{ij} (s_i - s_j)^\top (\dot{s}_i - \dot{s}_j).

Substitute \dot{s}_i = -[L S]_i + \beta R(s_i). After algebraic manipulation and using the fact that near equilibrium R(s_i) \approx [W S]_i, one can show that

\frac{d}{dt}\text{GNSI} = -2 (S - \mathbf{1}s^*)^\top L (S - \mathbf{1}s^*) + 2\beta (S - \mathbf{1}s^*)^\top W (S - \mathbf{1}s^*) - 2\lambda (\text{terms involving gradients}).

The first two terms combine to -2 (S - \mathbf{1}s^*)^\top (L - \beta W)(S - \mathbf{1}s^*). The matrix L - \beta W is positive definite when \beta < \beta_{\text{critical}}. The remaining terms involving \lambda are higher-order and negative semi-definite due to the decoupling effect. A full proof would require careful bounding, but the intuition is that the GNSI decreases as the system approaches the stable equilibrium. This property is confirmed numerically in the toy example.

A.4 Fisher Information and Criticality Detection

Let X(t) be a p-dimensional vector of peace indicators. Assume that at each time t, X(t) is drawn independently from an exponential family with density

f(x;\theta) = h(x) \exp\big( \theta^\top T(x) - A(\theta) \big),

where \theta \in \Theta \subseteq \mathbb{R}^d is the natural parameter, T(x) is a vector of sufficient statistics, and A(\theta) is the log-partition function.

The Fisher Information matrix is

F(\theta) = \mathbb{E}\left[ \left( \frac{\partial}{\partial\theta} \log f(X;\theta) \right) \left( \frac{\partial}{\partial\theta} \log f(X;\theta) \right)^\top \right] = \operatorname{Cov}[T(X)] = \nabla^2 A(\theta).

We define F_{\text{peace}}(t) = \operatorname{tr}(F(\theta(t))), which measures the total sensitivity of the distribution to changes in \theta.

Criticality detection: The system enters a region of poor signal‑to‑noise when F_{\text{peace}}(t) drops below a threshold. This threshold is determined empirically by analyzing historical crises. For instance, one could fit the exponential family to pre‑crisis data and compute the distribution of F_{\text{peace}} during the 30 days preceding each crisis. The 5th percentile of that distribution becomes F_{\text{critical}}. The choice of percentile balances false positives and missed detections; the extreme asymmetry of costs (false positive cost ≪ missed detection cost) suggests a conservative threshold (low percentile).

A.5 Wasserstein Distance and Epistemic Topology

For two probability distributions P and Q on \mathbb{R}^d with finite second moments, the 2‑Wasserstein distance is

W_2(P,Q) = \left( \inf_{\gamma \in \Gamma(P,Q)} \int \|x - y\|^2 \, d\gamma(x,y) \right)^{1/2},

where \Gamma(P,Q) denotes the set of all couplings (joint distributions) with marginals P and Q. When P and Q are multivariate Gaussians \mathcal{N}(\mu_1,\Sigma_1) and \mathcal{N}(\mu_2,\Sigma_2), the distance has a closed form:

W_2^2 = \|\mu_1 - \mu_2\|^2 + \operatorname{tr}\left( \Sigma_1 + \Sigma_2 - 2(\Sigma_1^{1/2} \Sigma_2 \Sigma_1^{1/2})^{1/2} \right).

In the GNRSA, epistemic states are approximated by Gaussian mixtures or particle filters from real‑time data. The Wasserstein distance provides a natural metric on the space of beliefs, and the threshold D_{\text{critical}} can be set based on historical misperception levels that preceded conflicts.

