Appendix B: Protocol Proofs and Security Analysis

B.1 Byzantine Fault Tolerance in the Canary Contract

The Canary Contract uses a Byzantine fault‑tolerant consensus protocol among M human nodes. We assume an adversary can corrupt up to f nodes, where f < M/3. The protocol ensures:

· Safety: No two honest nodes decide differently.
· Liveness: All honest nodes eventually decide if the network is synchronous.

The standard Practical Byzantine Fault Tolerance (PBFT) algorithm achieves these properties when M \ge 3f+1. In our setting, we require a threshold signature that aggregates authorizations; the condition |\{i: \text{authorize}(i)\}| \ge \lceil 2M/3 \rceil ensures that any decision has support from at least one honest node if f < M/3.

Proof sketch: Suppose a set of nodes with size \lceil 2M/3 \rceil agrees on authorization. Since the adversary controls at most \lfloor (M-1)/3 \rfloor nodes, the honest majority among that set is guaranteed. Hence, the decision reflects the will of at least one honest node, and no contradictory decision can be formed by a different set.

B.2 Liveness Failure Mode Analysis

When the number of reachable nodes q falls below \lceil 2M/3 \rceil, we enter degraded modes.

· Degraded Consensus Mode (\lceil M/2 \rceil \le q < \lceil 2M/3 \rceil): Requiring unanimous consent from reachable nodes prevents a minority of compromised nodes from forcing a false authorization. However, a single honest node can block a legitimate action. This trade‑off is acceptable because the system is already degraded; the priority is preventing catastrophic false positives. An adversary controlling one reachable node could veto, but they cannot force an action. The worst case is a denial‑of‑service attack, which is less harmful than an unauthorized launch.
· Fail‑Safe Mode (q < \lceil M/2 \rceil): With fewer than half the nodes reachable, any decision could be dominated by a small adversarial subset. The only safe default is to block all automated actions and rely on pre‑authorized defensive measures. Continuous alert broadcasts ensure that human operators are aware of the degradation and can attempt manual recovery.

These modes are derived from standard quorum theory and are designed to maximize safety under degraded conditions.

B.3 Threshold Cryptography Security

The multi‑vendor TEE architecture uses a k-of-n threshold signature scheme (e.g., using BLS signatures). Even if an adversary compromises up to k-1 TEEs, they cannot forge a valid proof. The choice of k and n should balance security and availability; e.g., k=2, n=3 ensures that at least two different vendors' TEEs must agree, reducing the risk of a single vendor's vulnerability being exploited. Post‑quantum signatures (CRYSTALS‑Dilithium) provide long‑term security against quantum attacks.

